<DOC><DOCNO> AP880706-0195 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1919EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-SBABill     07-06 0136</FIRST><SECOND>AM-SBA Bill,130</SECOND><HEAD>House Passes SBA Bill</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House on Wednesday passed 342-40 a billcontinuing the Small Business Administration's subsidy programs andrejecting President Reagan's call to end SBA direct loans.   The measure includes provisions giving aid to firms seeking tosell overseas, and banning SBA assistance for firms engaging inbusiness with South Africa.   The bill, which goes next to the Senate, authorizes $470 millionin SBA spending next year, $514 million in fiscal 1990 and $566 infiscal 1991. It also authorizes spending as necessary for disasterassistance loans.   Total SBA-supported loans would reach $3.7 billion next year,under the bill, up from about $3.2 billion this year.   Under Congress' multi-step spending process, the final levelsfor the SBA and its programs will be set later in appropriationsbills.</TEXT></DOC>